# Go Services ‚Äî Clean Architecture Guidelines

When adding or editing code in services (`upload`, `metadata`, `transcoding`), follow clean architecture and the structure below. Use **services/upload** as the reference for REST and gRPC.

## 1. Folder structure

```
services/<service-name>/
  cmd/
    server/
      main.go                    # Entry: load config, wire dependencies, start HTTP or gRPC server
  internal/
    application/
      ports/                     # Outbound interfaces (repository, storage, publisher, etc.)
      services/                  # Application services / use-cases (depend on ports, use domain)
    domain/
      entities/                  # Domain entities (structs, constructors; no external deps)
    adapters/
      http/                      # HTTP transport: controller + routes
        upload_controller.go
        routes/
          upload_route.go
      grpc/                      # gRPC transport: server implementation (controller)
        upload_controller.go
      postgres/                  # SQL persistence: implements repository ports
      object-storage/            # S3/MinIO: implements file-storage port
      rabbitmq/                  # Messaging: implements publisher port
```

- **Entry** (`cmd/server/main.go`): Load config (env or flags), build adapters ‚Üí inject into application services ‚Üí inject services into HTTP/gRPC controllers, register routes, start servers. No business logic in main.
- **Application**: Ports (interfaces) and services (use-cases) live under `internal/application/`. Services depend only on ports and domain entities.
- **Adapters**: All transport and persistence live under `internal/adapters/`, grouped by technology (http, grpc, postgres, object-storage, rabbitmq). HTTP and gRPC adapters are thin: parse request, call service, format response.

## 2. Domain entities

- Place under `internal/domain/entities/`; one file per entity (e.g. `video.go`, `upload.go`).
- **Structs** with exported fields; use constructors for new aggregates and keep status/consts in the same package.
- **Constructor**: `func NewX(...) *X` for new aggregates (set ID, timestamps, default status). Validate in the application service or at the edge if needed.
- No dependency on frameworks, DB, or HTTP/gRPC. Domain may depend only on standard library or shared **pkg** (e.g. `pkg/util` for `NullIfEmpty`).
- Package: `package entities`; export types, constructors, and status constants.

```go
// internal/domain/entities/video.go
package entities

type Video struct {
    ID        string
    UserID    string
    Title     string
    Status    string
    CreatedAt time.Time
    UpdatedAt time.Time
}

func NewVideo(userID, title string) *Video {
    now := time.Now()
    return &Video{ID: uuid.New().String(), UserID: userID, Title: title, Status: VideoStatusProcessing, CreatedAt: now, UpdatedAt: now}
}
```

## 3. Ports (outbound interfaces)

- Place under `internal/application/ports/`; one file per concern (e.g. `video_repository.go`, `file_storage_repository.go`, `upload_process_publisher.go`).
- **Interfaces** only; methods take/return **domain entities** (from `internal/domain/entities`) or primitives.
- Name by role: `VideoRepository`, `FileStorageRepository`, `UploadProcessPublisher`. Suffix with the role (Repository, Publisher, etc.).
- Ports are implemented by adapters under `internal/adapters/` (postgres, object-storage, rabbitmq, etc.).

```go
// internal/application/ports/video_repository.go
package ports

import (
    "context"
    "github.com/.../internal/domain/entities"
)

type VideoRepository interface {
    Create(ctx context.Context, v *entities.Video) error
    GetByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (*entities.Video, error)
    Update(ctx context.Context, v *entities.Video) error
}
```

## 4. Application services

- One file (or one per bounded context) under `internal/application/services/` (e.g. `upload_service.go`).
- **Constructor** receives **port interfaces** (repositories, storage, publisher), not concrete adapter types.
- Methods: create/load entities, call ports; return domain or errors. Use sentinel errors (e.g. `ErrFinalizeUpload`) and `fmt.Errorf("%w", err)` for wrapping.
- Validation that is use-case specific (e.g. allowed file extensions) can live in the service; keep domain free of I/O.
- No HTTP, gRPC, or database types; only domain entities, ports, and standard library (or shared `pkg`).
- Package: `package service`.

```go
// internal/application/services/upload_service.go
package service

type UploadService struct {
    videoRepo  ports.VideoRepository
    uploadRepo ports.UploadRepository
}

func NewUploadService(videoRepo ports.VideoRepository, uploadRepo ports.UploadRepository, ...) *UploadService {
    return &UploadService{videoRepo: videoRepo, uploadRepo: uploadRepo}
}

func (s *UploadService) RequestPresignURL(ctx context.Context, userID, title string) (string, string, error) {
    video := entities.NewVideo(userID, title)
    if err := s.videoRepo.Create(ctx, video); err != nil { return "", "", err }
    // ...
}
```

## 5. Controllers and routes (adapters)

- **HTTP**: Under `internal/adapters/http/`; `upload_controller.go` (package `controller`). Constructor receives the **service**. Parse request, call service, write HTTP response (status and JSON). Routes live under `internal/adapters/http/routes/` (e.g. `upload_route.go`) and expose `RegisterUploadRoutes(r chi.Router, c *controller.UploadController)`.
- **gRPC**: Under `internal/adapters/grpc/`; implement the generated gRPC server interface (e.g. `upload_controller.go`, package `grpcserver`). Constructor receives the **service**. In each RPC: validate request, call service method, return proto response.
- **Errors**: Map service errors to HTTP status codes (404, 400, 500) or gRPC codes. Do not expose internal errors in response bodies.
- Controllers are thin adapters: no business logic, only translation between transport and service.

## 6. Adapters (persistence and messaging)

- **Postgres**: Under `internal/adapters/postgres/`; one file per repository (e.g. `video_repository.go`, `upload_repository.go`). Implements `ports.VideoRepository`, `ports.UploadRepository`, etc. Constructor receives `*pgxpool.Pool`. Use `entities.*` and `pkg/util.NullIfEmpty` for optional string columns.
- **Object storage**: Under `internal/adapters/object-storage/`; `s3_repository.go`, `minio_repository.go` implementing `ports.FileStorageRepository`. Package: `objectstorage`.
- **Messaging**: Under `internal/adapters/rabbitmq/` (or similar); implements `ports.UploadProcessPublisher`. Package: `amqp` (or avoid clash with `pkg/rabbitmq`).
- Group by technology (postgres, object-storage, rabbitmq); main wires concrete adapters and passes interfaces into the service.

## 7. Entry and wiring (cmd/server/main.go)

- **Config**: Read from env (port, DB DSN, bucket, etc.). Use `pkg/config` if shared.
- **Wire**: Instantiate adapters (postgres repos, object-storage, rabbitmq publisher), then service with port interfaces, then HTTP controller and gRPC controller with the service. Call `routes.RegisterUploadRoutes(r, uploadController)`. Register gRPC server with `upload.RegisterUploadStateServiceServer(grpcServer, grpcserver.NewUploadStateController(uploadSvc))`.
- **Server**: Create HTTP router and gRPC server, register routes and gRPC service, then `ListenAndServe` and `grpcServer.Serve(lis)` (e.g. in a goroutine for gRPC).
- Keep main short; no business logic.

## 8. Naming and packages

- **Entities**: `Video`, `Upload` in `internal/domain/entities/` (package `entities`).
- **Ports**: `VideoRepository`, `FileStorageRepository` in `internal/application/ports/` (package `ports`).
- **Service**: `UploadService` in `internal/application/services/` (package `service`).
- **HTTP**: Controller and routes in `internal/adapters/http/` and `internal/adapters/http/routes/` (packages `controller`, `routes`).
- **gRPC**: Controller in `internal/adapters/grpc/` (package `grpcserver` to avoid clash with `google.golang.org/grpc`).
- **Adapters**: Postgres (package `postgres`), object-storage (package `objectstorage`), rabbitmq (package `amqp`). Implement port interfaces; names like `NewVideoRepository`, `NewS3Repository`, `NewRabbitMQUploadProcessPublisher`.

## 9. Shared code (pkg)

- **pkg/config**: Shared config loading (env, validation).
- **pkg/logger**: Structured logger used by controllers and adapters; avoid logging inside domain or application service.
- **pkg/util**: Shared helpers (e.g. `NullIfEmpty(s string) interface{}` for SQL NULL handling). Use across services.
- **pkg/rabbitmq**: Connection and publish/consume helpers; adapters in services use this and implement service-specific ports.
- **pkg/middleware**: HTTP middleware (auth, logging, recovery); gRPC interceptors if shared.
- **pkg/models**: Shared value objects or DTOs only if needed across services; keep domain in each service‚Äôs `internal/domain/entities/`.

## 10. Adding a new aggregate or capability

1. Add entity in `internal/domain/entities/` with struct and constructor.
2. Add or extend port interface in `internal/application/ports/` (e.g. `XRepository`).
3. Add or extend service in `internal/application/services/` that depends on the new port and entities.
4. Add or extend HTTP controller in `internal/adapters/http/` and route registration in `internal/adapters/http/routes/`, and/or gRPC controller in `internal/adapters/grpc/`.
5. Add or extend adapter in `internal/adapters/postgres/`, `object-storage/`, `rabbitmq/` (or new folder) implementing the port.
6. In `cmd/server/main.go`: instantiate the new adapter, inject into service, inject service into controller(s), register routes/gRPC, start server(s).
